<TITLE> BNP leader Ariful refused bail in Aug 21 case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 14 (bdnews24.com)A Dhaka court on Monday refused bail to BNP leader Ariful Islam in connection with the Aug 21 2004 grenade attack case. Defence counsel advocate Jainal Abedin Meshbah submitted the bail petition. Vacation judge of metropolitan sessions court Md Abdul Mazid rejected it. Arif, a Dhaka City Corporation councilor, was arrested on Sept 15 in connection with the 2001 bomb attack on a Communist Party of Bangladesh rally. Later he was taken into remand for nine days in two phases in November after being shown arrested in connection with the subsequent 2004 grenade attack on an Awami League rally. He was also taken into remand for grilling in several phases in connection with the bomb attack on the Narayanganj Awami League office. The Aug 21 2004 grenade attack on Bangabandhu Avenue killed at least 23 people and left scores injured during an Awami League rally, including prime minister Sheikh Hasina, who was then opposition leader. Some 22 people stand charged in a murder and explosives case, including former BNP state minister Abdus Salam Pintu, his brother Maolana Tajuddin, also the alleged grenade supplier, and Mufti Hannan, leader of banned Islamist outfit Harkat-ul-Jihad-al-Islami. b
